<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-321-475  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 321 475.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Feb 6 1989 v6 n5 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>User backing intensifies for short-haul microwave; technologyviewed as economical alternative.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cox, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A recent study by the market research firm International ResourceDevelopment Inc shows users are beginning to use microwave radiodata transmission products instead of private fiber lines andcarrier-based leased lines for short-haul communication needs.andO;Courtney Klinck, author of the report, projects sales ofshort-haul digital microwave products will be $375 million in1993, a considerable increase over 1988's $100 million in sales.andO;Early users of microwave radio links to connect local areanetworks and to support other high-bandwidth applications are: theSalt River Project Agriculture Improvement and Power District, thepublic power and water utility in Tempe, AZ; Harvard University;and Massachusetts General Hospital.andP;  Telecommunications managersat these institutions say microwave is economical and providesrelatively high bandwidth.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Microwave CommunicationsRadio CommunicationFiber OpticsTransmission LinesLeased LinesLocal CommunicationLocal Area Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>